content.description: Same start as Slot SDS. Once you are able to get to the original Slot start, traverse right until you reach the good dish and far right 15mm side pull. Throw up right hand about 2-3 feet to the shelf. Very burly final move. Top out straight over and you are done. Very fun route!
content.location: Hummingbird boulders. Left of the tree. Right hand start hold is four feet below the obvious slot start hold, and left hand is around four feet to the left from the right hand start hold.

content.description: Start on the jugs to the right of lunge and traverse left low on the start holds til you get to arête . Make this problem a little funner
content.location: Start on the warm up to the right of Lunge

content.description: Start with two hands on the jug on the far right of the slot boulder (you could heel hook the starting hold to match) or figure out a different sequence,  make a big move to the obvious sloper left match. Move left hand to dish.
content.location: Hummingbird Boulder right of the tree. start is just left of the tiny cave.

content.description:
Sit start to Slot (V6) five feet down and to the left of the stand slot start hold, with left hand on good sidepull finger jug and right hand on small 2-3 finger slopey crimp. The start is pretty spanned with a hidden good foot under the boulder. Bump right hand in to a vertical crimp sidepull then pull off a huge committing bump with your right hand to a baseball sized sloper hole a couple feet higher. From there, figure out some delicate beta into the start of Slot (V6) and finish up the same topout. Beta for the stand start may change depending on which hand you can get into the good part of the slot hold. According to Joe, this route is supposed to be a slight eliminate because you avoid the jug shelf to the left of the left starting side pull for the sit-start; the route flows better without it anyways.

Burly, delicate and perhaps a tad height dependent. Regardless, it's a super great route for those who climb the grade.
content.location: Left of the tree. Right hand start hold is four feet below the obvious slot start hold, and left hand is around four feet to the left from the right hand start hold.

content.description: Start at angled sloper slot left of tree, traverse in front of tree to right and use dish to top.
content.protection: Pads, preferably one on the ground and one against the tree.
content.location: Hummingbird Boulders, on the left boulder when you come up the trail.

content.description: Start with left hand in the best part of the slot and right hand crossed on the sloper to the left of the slot, same start at Slot (V6).Make your way out right on some side pulls and a good dish up high, the route finishes with a big move to the slopey lip where you’ll top out from. This route is a shorter version of Venga Bus (V8).

Start on the jug block on the southeastern corner of the right Hummingbird boulder. Traverse right to a good sidecling and then go straight up. Top out using whatever feet you can find. The walk-off should be apparent.
content.protection: The fall zone is flat, but the crux requires some commitment, which makes a pad good to have.
content.location: Look for the well-chalked jug block ~4 feet up, on the right Hummingbird boulder.

content.description: Start by crawling as far into the small cave as possible. You can start head first or feet first (doesn't really change the grade). If going feet first, use some OW trickery to turn around and invert. If going head first, make a couple of hard moves and then stem your way up. Either way, the crux is keeping your back off the ground.
content.protection: Maybe a blanket or small piece of carpet?
content.location: The tiny cave between the two boulders.

content.description: Really cool movement actually, one of the better problems at bishop peak. Directly to the left of the giant crack rail that is the start of Lunge.  Start on the two obvious opposing chalked holds directly below and left of start of lunge.  Put your feet some where move left hand up.  Then do a few bumps with right to good top out holds. Pretty fun moves.
content.location: Directly on arête left of lunge.
